Reference-contexts: This model is combined with a standard autoregressive vocal tract model to form an improved speech production model for voiced sounds. Similar combined models have been applied to the enhancement of speech corrupted by additive white Gaussian noise <ref> (Goh et al., 1998) </ref>, and to the modelling of general time series (Barnett et al., 1996). 3 Parameter estimation for the combined model is particularly difficult, since it requires estimates of the uncorrupted speech and glottal excitation signals to be available. <p> Most traditional methods approach these problems by assuming that the noise variance can be measured from speech-free segments of the observed signal, and various ad hoc estimation strategies for the model parameters (see, for example, <ref> (Goh et al., 1998) </ref>). Here a fully Bayesian framework is presented to solve elegantly the signal reconstruction, inverse filtering and parameter estimation problems simultaneously. The inferences required from the resulting posterior distribution are analytically intractable, and are hence approximated by Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) techniques.
